{"title_page": "Combat (newspaper)", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2007}}\n\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = Combat\n| editor          = <!-- up to |editor5= -->\n| editor_title    = <!-- up to |editor_title5= -->\n| category        = National Press\n| frequency       = daily\n| founder         = \n| founded         =December 1941\n| firstdate       = December 1941\n| finaldate       = August 1974\n| country         = {{FRA}}\n| based           = [[Paris]]\n| language        = [[French language|French]]\n| website         = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| issn            = \n| oclc            = \n}}\n\n'''''Combat''''' was a [[France|French]] [[newspaper]] created during the [[Second World War]]. It was founded in 1941 as a clandestine newspaper of the [[French Resistance|Resistance]]. Following the liberation, the main participants in the publication included [[Albert Ollivier]], [[Jean-Paul de Dadelsen]], [[Jean Bloch-Michel]] (1912\u20131987), and [[Georges Altschuler]] [[:fr:Georges Altschuler|(fr)]]. Among leading contributors were [[Jean-Paul Sartre]], [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]], [[Emmanuel Mounier]], [[Raymond Aron]] and [[Pierre Herbart]] [[:fr:Pierre Herbart|(fr)]].<ref>Sylvie Courtine-Denamy, Le souci du monde. Dialogue entre Hannah Arendt et quelques-uns de ses contemporains, Vrin, 1999, p. 81</ref> From 1943 to 1947, its editor-in-chief was [[Albert Camus]].<ref>J. Levi-Valensi (ed), ''Camus at Combat'' Princeton University Press, 2006</ref> Its production was directed by [[Andr\u00e9 Bollier]] until [[Milice]] repression led to his death.\n\nIn August 1944, ''Combat'' took the headquarters of ''[[L'Intransigeant]]'', 100 [[Rue R\u00e9aumur]] [[:fr:Rue R\u00e9aumur|(fr)]] in Paris, while [[Albert Camus]] became its [[editor in chief]]. The newspaper's production run decreased from 185,000 copies in January 1945 to 150,000 in August of the same year:{{Clarify|date=February 2009}} it wasn't able to rival with others established newspapers (the Communist daily ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'' was publishing at the time 500,000 copies). During 1946, ''Combat'' was opposed to the \"game of the parties\" claiming to rebuild France, and thus became closer to [[Charles de Gaulle]] without, however, becoming the official voice of his movement.\n\nLoyal to its origins, ''Combat'' tried to become the place of expression for those who believed in creating a popular non-Communist [[left wing|Left]] movement in France. In July 1948 (more than a year after the May 1947 crisis and the expulsion of the [[French Communist Party|Communist Party]] (ministers) from the government), [[Victor Fay]] [[:de:Victor Fay|(de)]], a [[Marxist]] activist, took over ''Combat'' 's direction, but he failed to stop the newspaper's evolution towards more popular subjects and less political information.\n\nIn 1950, it hosted a debate about the [[Notre-Dame Affair]] stimulated by a vehement letter by [[Andr\u00e9 Breton]] in response to the editor [[Louis Pauwels]].<ref name=\"Boucharenc05\">Myriam Boucharenc (2005) [https://books.google.com/books?id=uYKf2PLK1BgC ''L'universel reportage''], pp. 94-6</ref><ref name=\"Breton50NotreDame\" />\n\n[[Philippe Tesson]] [[:fr:Philippe Tesson|(fr)]] became editor in chief from 1960 to 1974. [[Henri Smadja]] [[:fr:Henri Smadja|(fr)]] had thought Tesson could be a perfect puppet-editor but Smadja's situation, in part because of the [[Tunisia]]n regime, got worse. In March 1974, Philippe Tesson created ''[[Le Quotidien de Paris]]'' (1974\u20131996), which he had conceived as the successor of ''Combat''.\n\nDuring the [[May 1968 in France|May 1968 crisis]], ''Combat'' supported the student movement although from a [[Stalinist]] point of view, through the signatures of the likes of [[Jacques-Arnaud Penent]] [[:fr:Jacques-Arnaud Penent|(fr)]]. On 3 June, it published a falsified version of the ''Address to All Workers'' by the [[Council for Maintaining the Occupations]], removing the references to the [[Situationist International]] and the attacks against the Stalinists.<ref name=\"Vienet68\" /><ref name=\"Knabb 2006\" />  Henri Smadja committed suicide on 14 July 1974, and ''Combat'' definitively ceased to be published the following month.\n\n==See also==\n*[[France in the twentieth century]]\n*[[French Fourth Republic|Fourth Republic]] (1946\u20131958)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Breton50NotreDame\">[[Andr\u00e9 Breton]] (1950) [http://juralibertaire.over-blog.com/article-le-scandale-de-notre-dame-41681161.html \"Lettre a Louis Pauwels\" sur le 'scandale\" de Notre Dame,'\"] ''Combat'', April 12, 1950, ''OC III'', pp. 1024-5</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Vienet68\">[[Ren\u00e9 Vi\u00e9net]] (1968) ''Enrag\u00e9s et situationnistes dans le mouvement des occupations'', chapter 8 ''[http://www.cddc.vt.edu/sionline/si/enrages08.html The \"Council for Maintaining the Occupations\" and Councilist Tendencies]'' (Paris: Gallimard) Translated by Loren Goldner and [[Paul Sieveking]]; {{oclc|13724457}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Knabb 2006\">Authentic version: ''[http://www.cddc.vt.edu/sionline/si/address.html Address to All Workers]'' by [[Situationist International|Enrag\u00e9s-Situationist International Committee]], Council for Maintaining the Occupations. Paris, 30 May 1968.<div style=\"margin-left:2em\">Translated and reprinted in the book, ''Situationist International Anthology,'' translated by [[Ken Knabb]], Bureau of Public Secrets (2006); {{oclc|124093356}}</div></ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34501455d/date ''Combat''] issues (1941\u20131944 only) online in [[Gallica]], the digital library of the [[BnF]]\n* [http://www.matisse.lettres.free.fr/artdeblamer/tcombat.htm Albert Camus' editorial] on 8 August 1945 concerning the [[Hiroshima bombing]] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Combat (Newspaper)}}\n[[Category:1974 disestablishments in France]]\n[[Category:Publications disestablished in 1974]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:French resistance publications]]\n[[Category:Newspapers of the Vichy regime]]\n[[Category:Contemporary French history]]\n[[Category:Underground press in World War II]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2007}}\n\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = Combat\n| editor          = <!-- up to |editor5= -->\n| editor_title    = <!-- up to |editor_title5= -->\n| category        = National Press\n| frequency       = daily\n| founder         = \n| founded         =December 1941\n| firstdate       = December 1941\n| finaldate       = August 1974\n| country         = {{FRA}}\n| based           = [[Paris]]\n| language        = [[French language|French]]\n| website         = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| issn            = \n| oclc            = \n}}\n\n'''''Combat''''' was a [[France|French]] [[newspaper]] created during the [[Second World War]]. It was founded in 1941 as a clandestine newspaper of the [[French Resistance|Resistance]]. Following the liberation, the main participants in the publication included [[Albert Ollivier]], [[Jean-Paul de Dadelsen]], [[Jean Bloch-Michel]] (1912\u20131987), and [[Georges Altschuler]] [[:fr:Georges Altschuler|(fr)]]. Among leading contributors were [[Jean-Paul Sartre]], [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]], [[Emmanuel Mounier]], [[Raymond Aron]] and [[Pierre Herbart]] [[:fr:Pierre Herbart|(fr)]].<ref>Sylvie Courtine-Denamy, Le souci du monde. Dialogue entre Hannah Arendt et quelques-uns de ses contemporains, Vrin, 1999, p. 81</ref> From 1943 to 1947, its editor-in-chief was [[Albert Camus]].<ref>J. Levi-Valensi (ed), ''Camus at Combat'' Princeton University Press, 2006</ref> Its production was directed by [[Andr\u00e9 Bollier]] until [[Milice]] repression led to his death.\n\nIn August 1944, ''Combat'' took the headquarters of ''[[L'Intransigeant]]'', 100 [[Rue R\u00e9aumur]] [[:fr:Rue R\u00e9aumur|(fr)]] in Paris, while [[Albert Camus]] became its [[editor in chief]]. The newspaper's production run decreased from 185,000 copies in January 1945 to 150,000 in August of the same year:{{Clarify|date=February 2009}} it wasn't able to rival with others established newspapers (the Communist daily ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'' was publishing at the time 500,000 copies). During 1946, ''Combat'' was opposed to the \"game of the parties\" claiming to rebuild France, and thus became closer to [[Charles de Gaulle]] without, however, becoming the official voice of his movement.\n\nLoyal to its origins, ''Combat'' tried to become the place of expression for those who believed in creating a popular non-Communist [[left wing|Left]] movement in France. In July 1948 (more than a year after the May 1947 crisis and the expulsion of the [[French Communist Party|Communist Party]] (ministers) from the government), [[Victor Fay]] [[:de:Victor Fay|(de)]], a [[Marxist]] activist, took over ''Combat'' 's direction, but he failed to stop the newspaper's evolution towards more popular subjects and less political information.\n\nIn 1950, it hosted a debate about the [[Notre-Dame Affair]] stimulated by a vehement letter by [[Andr\u00e9 Breton]] in response to the editor [[Louis Pauwels]].<ref name=\"Boucharenc05\">Myriam Boucharenc (2005) [https://books.google.com/books?id=uYKf2PLK1BgC ''L'universel reportage''], pp. 94-6</ref><ref name=\"Breton50NotreDame\" />\n\n[[Philippe Tesson]] [[:fr:Philippe Tesson|(fr)]] became editor in chief from 1960 to 1974. [[Henri Smadja]] [[:fr:Henri Smadja|(fr)]] had thought Tesson could be a perfect puppet-editor but Smadja's situation, in part because of the [[Tunisia]]n regime, got worse. In March 1974, Philippe Tesson created ''[[Le Quotidien de Paris]]'' (1974\u20131996), which he had conceived as the successor of ''Combat''.\n\nDuring the [[May 1968 in France|May 1968 crisis]], ''Combat'' supported the student movement although from a [[Stalinist]] point of view, through the signatures of the likes of [[Jacques-Arnaud Penent]] [[:fr:Jacques-Arnaud Penent|(fr)]]. On 3 June, it published a falsified version of the ''Address to All Workers'' by the [[Council for Maintaining the Occupations]], removing the references to the [[Situationist International]] and the attacks against the Stalinists.<ref name=\"Vienet68\" /><ref name=\"Knabb 2006\" />  Henri Smadja committed suicide on 14 July 1974, and ''Combat'' definitively ceased to be published the following month.\n\n==See also==\n*[[France in the twentieth century]]\n*[[French Fourth Republic|Fourth Republic]] (1946\u20131958)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Breton50NotreDame\">[[Andr\u00e9 Breton]] (1950) [http://juralibertaire.over-blog.com/article-le-scandale-de-notre-dame-41681161.html \"Lettre a Louis Pauwels\" sur le 'scandale\" de Notre Dame,'\"] ''Combat'', April 12, 1950, ''OC III'', pp. 1024-5</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Vienet68\">[[Ren\u00e9 Vi\u00e9net]] (1968) ''Enrag\u00e9s et situationnistes dans le mouvement des occupations'', chapter 8 ''[http://www.cddc.vt.edu/sionline/si/enrages08.html The \"Council for Maintaining the Occupations\" and Councilist Tendencies]'' (Paris: Gallimard) Translated by Loren Goldner and [[Paul Sieveking]]; {{oclc|13724457}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Knabb 2006\">Authentic version: ''[http://www.cddc.vt.edu/sionline/si/address.html Address to All Workers]'' by [[Situationist International|Enrag\u00e9s-Situationist International Committee]], Council for Maintaining the Occupations. Paris, 30 May 1968.<div style=\"margin-left:2em\">Translated and reprinted in the book, ''Situationist International Anthology,'' translated by [[Ken Knabb]], Bureau of Public Secrets (2006); {{oclc|124093356}}</div></ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34501455d/date ''Combat''] issues (1941\u20131944 only) online in [[Gallica]], the digital library of the [[BnF]]\n* [http://www.matisse.lettres.free.fr/artdeblamer/tcombat.htm Albert Camus' editorial] on 8 August 1945 concerning the [[Hiroshima bombing]] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Combat (Newspaper)}}\n[[Category:1974 disestablishments in France]]\n[[Category:Publications disestablished in 1974]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:French resistance publications]]\n[[Category:Newspapers of the Vichy regime]]\n[[Category:Contemporary French history]]\n[[Category:Underground press in World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combat_(newspaper)"}
{"title_page": "Mark Azbel", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Israeli physicist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Mark Azbel\n| native_name       = \u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a \u042f\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c\n| native_name_lang  = Russian\n| image             = Mark Azbel 2019 July 001.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = Mark Azbel in 2019\n| caption           = Mark Azbel in 2019\n| birth_name        = Mark Yakovlevich Azbel\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1932|5|12}}\n| birth_place       = Kharkov (now [[Kharkiv]]), Ukrainian SSR, USSR\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|3|31|1932|5|12}}<ref>[http://newsru.co.il/israel/01apr2020/azbel_121.html \u0412 \u0418\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043b\u0435 \u0443\u043c\u0435\u0440 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a \u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a \u0410\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c]</ref>\n| death_place       = [[Israel]]\n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| other_names       = \n| siglum            = \n| alma_mater        = [[National University of Kharkiv]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Lev Landau]]\n| influenced        = [[Douglas Hofstadter]]\n| workplaces        = [[Tel Aviv University]]\n[[Moscow State University]]\n[[National University of Kharkiv]]\n| fields            = [[Solid-state physics]]\n}}\n\n'''Mark Yakovlevich Azbel''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a \u042f\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c}}; 12 May 1932 \u2014 31 March 2020) was a Soviet and Israeli physicist.<ref>[http://ferro.phys.msu.ru/study/phys/spets/04-4.html \u0420\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0451\u0440\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0430 \u00ab\u0414\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0433\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\u00bb]</ref> He was a member of the [[American Physical Society]].\n\nBetween 1956 and 1958, he experimentally demonstrated [[Cyclotron resonance|cyclotron resonance]] in metals, and worked out its theoretical basis.<ref>[http://www.jetp.ac.ru/cgi-bin/dn/e_006_06_1126.pdf Theory of Cyclotron Resonance in Metals]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=o5Yb7Q2t1qIC&pg=PA263&lpg=PA263&dq= Jen\u00f6 S\u00f3lyom \u00abFundamentals of the Physics of Solids: Volume II: Electronic Properties\u00bb]</ref><ref>[https://www.spiedigitallibrary.org/ebooks/FG/Field-Guide-to-Solid-State-Physics/AzbelKaner-Cyclotron-Resonance/AzbelKaner-Cyclotron-Resonance/10.1117/3.2510243.ch49?SSO=1 Azbel \u2013 Kaner Cyclotron Resonance]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=FOOyBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA348&lpg=PA348&dq= Rudolf Herrmann, Uwe Preppernau \u00abElektronen im Kristall\u00bb]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAzbel was born in a family of physicians.<ref>[http://histpol.pl.ua/ru/petrovskij-poltavskij-kadetskij-korpus/personal-ppkk/zakonouchiteli-svyashchennosluzhiteli-ppkk?id=1159 \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u044b]</ref> From 1941, aged 9 to 12, he lived in war evacuation ([[Siberia]]).\n\nIn 1944, the family returned to Kharkiv. In 1948 he graduated from high school and in the same year entered the [[National University of Kharkiv]]. After graduation, he taught mathematics at evening school.\n\nIn 1958, he defended his doctorate (Doctor of Physical and Mathematical Sciences) under the supervision of [[Lev Landau]] and [[Pyotr Kapitsa]].<ref>[http://www.ufn.ru/ru/authors/azbel_m_ya/ \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0438, \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0443\u0435\u043c\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442\u0435 \u0423\u0424\u041d]</ref><ref>[http://www2.tau.ac.il/Person/exact/physics/researcher.asp?id=acjgeedec   Professor Mark Azbel]</ref> In 1964 he began working at [[Moscow State University]] and concurrently as a section chair  at the [[Landau Institute for Theoretical Physics]].\n\nIn 1972, Azbel applied for emigration from the Soviet Union to Israel, and in 1973 (a full four years before leaving the Soviet Union) became a lecturer at [[Tel Aviv University]], where he initially gave his lectures by telephone. \n\nHaving been refused exit permission from the Soviet Union, he participated in the movement of [[refusenik]]s in the USSR in the mid-seventies.<ref>Refusenik, trapped in the Soviet Union / Mark Ya. Azbel; edited by Grace Pierce Forbes.   Boston: Houghton Mifflin co., 1981,   {{ISBN|0-395-30226-9}}</ref> Azbel finally emigrated from the USSR in 1977 and was appointed Professor at [[Tel Aviv University]].<ref>[http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,907505,00.html Education: Physics by Phone]</ref> He lived in Israel until his death in 2020.\n\n== Scientific contributions==\nAzbel was a theoretical physicist.  His areas of study included the quantum physics of electrons in metals, and made the first prediction of cyclotron resonance in metals, now widely known as the Azbel-Kaner resonance.\n\nIn an important 1964 article,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Azbel|first=Mark|date=|title=Energy Spectrum of a Conduction Electron in a Magnetic Field|url=|journal=Journal of Experimental and Theoretical Physics|volume=19|pages=634|via=}}</ref> Azbel made conjectures about the nature of the Harper spectrum that contributed to the discovery of the [[Hofstadter butterfly]] in 1974.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Satija, Indubala I., 1952-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/957689639|title=Butterfly in the quantum world : the story of the most fascinating quantum fractal|others=Hofstadter, Douglas R., 1945-, Morgan & Claypool Publishers,, Institute of Physics (Great Britain),|isbn=978-1-68174-117-8|location=San Rafael [California] (40 Oak Drive, San Rafael, CA, 94903, USA)|oclc=957689639}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n*{{Cite book|last=Mark Azbel|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/6735540|title=Refusenik, trapped in the Soviet Union|date=1981|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|others=Forbes, Grace Pierce.|isbn=0-395-30226-9|location=Boston|oclc=6735540}}\n\n*{{Cite book||others=Ilia M. Lifshits, Mark Ya. Azbel, Moisei I. Kaganov|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/797018485|title=Electron Theory of Metals.|date=1973|publisher=Consultants Bureau|isbn=9780306108730|oclc=797018485}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.itp.ac.ru/ru/persons/azbel-mark-yakovlevich/ \u0418\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u0442\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0444\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0438\u043c.   \u041b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0443]\n* [http://www.regels.org/wave-corpusc-experiment1.htm \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442: \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u043e\u0431\u0441\u0443\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435. \u0414\u0435-\u0411\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043b\u044c,  \u041b\u0435\u043e\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447,  \u0424\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0442,  \u0410\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c,  \u0421\u0430\u0445\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432]\n* [https://jewish.ru/ru/people/science/192613/ \u0424\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0445\u0430\u043c, \u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kharkiv]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Tel Aviv University faculty]]\n[[Category:National University of Kharkiv alumni]]\n[[Category:Soviet physicists]]\n[[Category:Israeli physicists]]\n[[Category:Refuseniks]]\n[[Category:American Physical Society]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Israeli physicist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Mark Azbel\n| native_name       = \u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a \u042f\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c\n| native_name_lang  = Russian\n| image             = Mark Azbel 2019 July 001.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = Mark Azbel in 2019\n| caption           = Mark Azbel in 2019\n| birth_name        = Mark Yakovlevich Azbel\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1932|5|12}}\n| birth_place       = Kharkov (now [[Kharkiv]]), Ukrainian SSR, USSR\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|3|31|1932|5|12}}<ref>[http://newsru.co.il/israel/01apr2020/azbel_121.html \u0412 \u0418\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043b\u0435 \u0443\u043c\u0435\u0440 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a \u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a \u0410\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c]</ref>\n| death_place       = [[Israel]]\n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| other_names       = \n| siglum            = \n| alma_mater        = [[National University of Kharkiv]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Lev Landau]]\n| influenced        = [[Douglas Hofstadter]]\n| workplaces        = [[Tel Aviv University]]\n[[Moscow State University]]\n[[National University of Kharkiv]]\n| fields            = [[Solid-state physics]]\n}}\n\n'''Mark Yakovlevich Azbel''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a \u042f\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c}}; 12 May 1932 \u2014 31 March 2020) was a Soviet and Israeli physicist.<ref>[http://ferro.phys.msu.ru/study/phys/spets/04-4.html \u0420\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0451\u0440\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0430 \u00ab\u0414\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0433\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\u00bb]</ref> He was a member of the [[American Physical Society]].\n\nBetween 1956 and 1958, he experimentally demonstrated [[cyclotron resonance|Cyclotron resonance]] in metals, and worked out its theoretical basis.ref>[http://www.jetp.ac.ru/cgi-bin/dn/e_006_06_1126.pdf Theory of Cyclotron Resonance in Metals]</ref>, \u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0437\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0435 \u0447\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e \u044f\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0437\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0430 \u0410\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044f \u2014 \u041a\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=o5Yb7Q2t1qIC&pg=PA263&lpg=PA263&dq= Jen\u00f6 S\u00f3lyom \u00abFundamentals of the Physics of Solids: Volume II: Electronic Properties\u00bb]</ref><ref>[https://www.spiedigitallibrary.org/ebooks/FG/Field-Guide-to-Solid-State-Physics/AzbelKaner-Cyclotron-Resonance/AzbelKaner-Cyclotron-Resonance/10.1117/3.2510243.ch49?SSO=1 Azbel \u2013 Kaner Cyclotron Resonance]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=FOOyBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA348&lpg=PA348&dq= Rudolf Herrmann, Uwe Preppernau \u00abElektronen im Kristall\u00bb]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAzbel was born in a family of physicians.<ref>[http://histpol.pl.ua/ru/petrovskij-poltavskij-kadetskij-korpus/personal-ppkk/zakonouchiteli-svyashchennosluzhiteli-ppkk?id=1159 \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0432\u044b]</ref> From 1941, aged 9 to 12, he lived in war evacuation ([[Siberia]]).\n\nIn 1944, the family returned to Kharkiv. In 1948 he graduated from high school and in the same year entered the [[National University of Kharkiv]]. After graduation, he taught mathematics at evening school.\n\nIn 1958, he defended his doctorate (Doctor of Physical and Mathematical Sciences) under the supervision of [[Lev Landau]] and [[Pyotr Kapitsa]].<ref>[http://www.ufn.ru/ru/authors/azbel_m_ya/ \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0438, \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0443\u0435\u043c\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442\u0435 \u0423\u0424\u041d]</ref><ref>[http://www2.tau.ac.il/Person/exact/physics/researcher.asp?id=acjgeedec   Professor Mark Azbel]</ref> In 1964 he began working at [[Moscow State University]] and concurrently as a section chair  at the [[Landau Institute for Theoretical Physics]].\n\nIn 1972, Azbel applied for emigration from the Soviet Union to Israel, and in 1973 (a full four years before leaving the Soviet Union) became a lecturer at [[Tel Aviv University]], where he initially gave his lectures by telephone. \n\nHaving been refused exit permission from the Soviet Union, he participated in the movement of [[refusenik]]s in the USSR in the mid-seventies.<ref>Refusenik, trapped in the Soviet Union / Mark Ya. Azbel; edited by Grace Pierce Forbes.   Boston: Houghton Mifflin co., 1981,   {{ISBN|0-395-30226-9}}</ref> Azbel finally emigrated from the USSR in 1977 and was appointed Professor at [[Tel Aviv University]].<ref>[http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,907505,00.html Education: Physics by Phone]</ref> He lived in Israel until his death in 2020.\n\n== Scientific contributions==\nAzbel was a theoretical physicist.  His areas of study included the quantum physics of electrons in metals, and made the first prediction of cyclotron resonance in metals, now widely known as the Azbel-Kaner resonance.\n\nIn an important 1964 article,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Azbel|first=Mark|date=|title=Energy Spectrum of a Conduction Electron in a Magnetic Field|url=|journal=Journal of Experimental and Theoretical Physics|volume=19|pages=634|via=}}</ref> Azbel made conjectures about the nature of the Harper spectrum that contributed to the discovery of the [[Hofstadter butterfly]] in 1974.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Satija, Indubala I., 1952-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/957689639|title=Butterfly in the quantum world : the story of the most fascinating quantum fractal|others=Hofstadter, Douglas R., 1945-, Morgan & Claypool Publishers,, Institute of Physics (Great Britain),|isbn=978-1-68174-117-8|location=San Rafael [California] (40 Oak Drive, San Rafael, CA, 94903, USA)|oclc=957689639}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n*{{Cite book|last=Mark Azbel|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/6735540|title=Refusenik, trapped in the Soviet Union|date=1981|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|others=Forbes, Grace Pierce.|isbn=0-395-30226-9|location=Boston|oclc=6735540}}\n\n*{{Cite book||others=Ilia M. Lifshits, Mark Ya. Azbel, Moisei I. Kaganov|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/797018485|title=Electron Theory of Metals.|date=1973|publisher=Consultants Bureau|isbn=9780306108730|oclc=797018485}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.itp.ac.ru/ru/persons/azbel-mark-yakovlevich/ \u0418\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u0442\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0444\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0438\u043c.   \u041b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0443]\n* [http://www.regels.org/wave-corpusc-experiment1.htm \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442: \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u043e\u0431\u0441\u0443\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435. \u0414\u0435-\u0411\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043b\u044c,  \u041b\u0435\u043e\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447,  \u0424\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0442,  \u0410\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c,  \u0421\u0430\u0445\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432]\n* [https://jewish.ru/ru/people/science/192613/ \u0424\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0445\u0430\u043c, \u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kharkiv]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Tel Aviv University faculty]]\n[[Category:National University of Kharkiv alumni]]\n[[Category:Soviet physicists]]\n[[Category:Israeli physicists]]\n[[Category:Refuseniks]]\n[[Category:American Physical Society]]\n", "name_user": "Glen Worthey", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Azbel"}
